-- Montana-Dakota Utilities Adds Two Wind Farms, Adds 30 Megawatts Capacity
-- Andrew Herndon
-- 2010-06-29T02:06:50Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-29/montana-dakota-utilities-adds-two-wind-farms-adds-30-megawatts-capacity.html

          
          
                  June 28 (Bloomberg New Energy Finance) -- Montana-Dakota
Utilities Co., a division of  MDU Resources , has commissioned two
new wind farms in Montana and North Dakota, adding 30 megawatts
to the companyâ€™s power generation capacity.  
 The 19.5 megawatt Cedar Hills wind farm near Rhame, North
Dakota and a 10.5 megawatt expansion to the Diamond Willow
project near Baker, Montana have entered commercial operation,
the utility said in a statement published on Business Wire.  
 Both projects are located on leased land. The first 18
megawatt phase of Diamond Willow started operating in 2007.  
 Montana-Dakota said it has invested almost $130 million to
date in wind generation and other renewable energy projects to
serve its customers in Montana, South Dakota, and North Dakota.  
